al solution notes mention: A* Search Algorithm.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cblockquote\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cp\\u003eAlgoForge explanations are original teaching notes. Always open the \\u003ca href=\\\\\\\"https://leetcode.com/problems/sliding-puzzle/\\\\\\\"\\u003eofficial problem statement on LeetCode\\u003c/a\\u003e for constraints and examples.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/blockquote\\u003e\\\\n\\\"}}]]}]\\n37:T4d5,\\u003ch2\\u003eInterview approach for Sliding Puzzle\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003eOpening (30–60 seconds)\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eClarify inputs/outputs and edge cases (empty input, single element, duplicates, overflow).\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eState a \\u003cstrong\\u003ebrute force\\u003c/strong\\u003e so the interviewer knows you can solve it naively.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003ePropose the \\u003cstrong\\u003eoptimal direction\\u003c/strong\\u003e tied to \\u003cstrong\\u003ea search algorithm\\u003c/strong\\u003e.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003eCore solution narrative\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003col\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eDefine the \\u003cstrong\\u003estate\\u003c/strong\\u003e you track (pointers, DP cell, set membership, stack top, etc.).\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eExplain the \\u003cstrong\\u003etransition\\u003c/strong\\u003e when you process the next element.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCall out \\u003cstrong\\u003etime\\u003c/strong\\u003e (O((m * n) * (m * n)!)) and \\u003cstrong\\u003espace\\u003c/strong\\u003e (O((m * n) * (m * n)!)) before coding.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCode cleanly; narrate variable names.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ol\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003eWhat interviewers listen for\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCorrectness on edge cases\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eComplexity honesty\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eAbility to discuss \\u003cstrong\\u003etrade-offs\\u003c/strong\\u003e (e.g., hash map space vs. sort + two pointers)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003ch3\\u003eFollow-up questions they may ask\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCan you solve it with less memory?\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eWhat if the input stream is infinite / doesn't fit in RAM?\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eHow would tests look for adversarial inputs?\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n27:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",\\\"interview\\\",{\\\"id\\\":\\\"interview\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-xl font-bold\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"Interview Walkthrough\\\"}],false]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"prose-af\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"$37\\\"}}]]}]\\n28:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",\\\"optimized\\\",{\\\"id\\\":\\\"optimized\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-xl font-bold\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"Optimized Approach\\\"}],false]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"prose-af\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003ch2\\u003eOptimized solution notes\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe reference solutions on AlgoForge target \\u003cstrong\\u003eO((m * n) * (m * n)!)\\u003c/strong\\u003e time and \\u003cstrong\\u003eO((m * n) * (m * n)!)\\u003c/strong\\u003e space.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ch3\\u003ePattern focus: a search algorithm\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cp\\u003eUse the pattern as a checklist:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ea search algorithm\\u003c/strong\\u003e — confirm the invariant holds after each step\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMultiple methods appear in the source solutions — compare them and explain when each is preferable.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ch3\\u003eImplementation tips\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003ePrefer readable names over micro-optimizations in interviews.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003eExtract helpers only when they clarify (e.g., expan\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"d-around-center, DFS visit).\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003eAfter AC-level logic, re-scan for off-by-one and null checks.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\\\n\\\"}}]]}]\\n29:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",\\\"complexity\\\",{\\\"id\\\":\\\"complexity\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-xl font-bold\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"Complexity Analysis\\\"}],false]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"prose-af\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003ch2\\u003eComplexity\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctable\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cthead\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctr\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cth\\u003eMeasure\\u003c/th\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cth\\u003eBound\\u003c/th\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/thead\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctbody\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctr\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctd\\u003eTime\\u003c/td\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctd\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eO((m * n) * (m * n)!)\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/td\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctr\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctd\\u003eSpace\\u003c/td\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ctd\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eO((m * n) * (m * n)!)\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/td\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/tbody\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/table\\u003e\\\\n\\u003ch3\\u003eHow to justify this in an interview\\u003c/h3\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eTime:\\u003c/strong\\u003e count loops, map/set operations, and recursive branching; state average vs worst case if relevant.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSpace:\\u003c/strong\\u003e include hash maps, recursion stack, and output allocation when the problem asks for it.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIf your implementation differs from the reference, re-derive big-O from \\u003cem\\u003eyour\\u003c/em\\u003e code — never memorize a complexity you cannot defend.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\\\n\\\"}}]]}]\\n2a:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",\\\"common-mistakes\\\",{\\\"id\\\":\\\"common-mistakes\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"h2\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-xl font-bold\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"Common Mistakes\\\"}],false]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"prose-af\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"\\u003ch2\\u003eCommon mistakes on Sliding Puzzle\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\\\n\\u003col\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSkipping edge cases\\u003c/strong\\u003e — empty collections, single-element inputs, max constraints.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eWrong invariant\\u003c/strong\\u003e for a search algorithm — updating state too early or too late.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eMutating input unexpectedly\\u003c/strong\\u003e when the problem forbids it.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eOff-by-one\\u003c/strong\\u003e in windows, ranges, or binary search bounds.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eIgnoring overflow / precision\\u003c/strong\\u003e for integer arithmetic problems.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eOverengineering\\u003c/strong\\u003e — jumping to an advanced structure when a simpler approach works.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\\\n\\u003c/ol\\u003e\\\\n\\\"